 sufficient leadership on environmental matters to be trusted to make weighty decisions with implications for public and environmental health. The first comprehensive study of the varying responses to golf-related environmental issues, it is based on extensive empirical work, including research into historical materials and interviews with stakeholders in golf such as course superintendents, protesters and health professionals. The authors examine golf as a sport and as a global industry, drawing on and contributing to literatures pertaining to environmental sociology, global social movements, institutional change, corporate environmentalism and the sociology of sport.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGolf coursesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSociology (General). 0aSports and globalization. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Sociology of Sports.2bisacsh  acorporate.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  agolf.  ainstitutional change.  aorganic.  apolicy.  asocial movements.  asociology.1 aMillington, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilson, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526107039zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526107039zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526107039/original  a978-3-11-128282-4 Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA